description:
### Problem to solve

The 'Project security status' report found on the Instance & Group level Security Dashboards should reflect same Standalone Vulnerability data used to populate the Vulnerability list. It should also not time-out every time it loads (ideally). 

### Further details

The decision was made as part of the Standalone Vulnerabilities MVC to leave this report back by the original "findings" data. While it was acknowledged at the time that this could be confusing for customers, due to time constraints we're choosing to address this data source in future iteration.

### Proposal

A new GraphQL endpoint was created as part of https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/213623: `ee/app/assets/javascripts/security_dashboard/graphql/get_instance_security_dashboard_projects.query.graphql`

This issue reflects the ~frontend work required to hook that endpoint up to the reports on the Instance and Group level dashboards. 

### Implementation plan 

Taken from https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/213623#note_390130264
- [x] Replace the old query and use the one provided [here](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/213623#note_388766468). Here is the query file that is responsible for the query: `ee/app/assets/javascripts/security_dashboard/graphql/get_instance_security_dashboard_projects.query.graphql`. We'll need to remove the `...VulnerabilitySeveritiesCount` part.
- [x] Right now the severities are attached to the project object and inside `ee/app/assets/javascripts/security_dashboard/components/first_class_vulnerability_severities.vue` we have a few methods responsible for mapping the data appropriately. The following is the biggest chunk which normalises the data.


```
    findProjectsForGroup(group) {
      if (group.type === severityGroupTypes.A) {
        return this.projects.filter(
          project =>
            Object.values(project.vulnerabilitySeveritiesCount || {})
              .filter(i => isNumber(i))
              .reduce(sum, 0) === 0,
        );
      }

      return this.projects
        .filter(project =>
          group.severityLevels.some(level => project.vulnerabilitySeveritiesCount?.[level] > 0),
        )
        .map(project => ({
          ...project,
          mostSevereVulnerability: this.findMostSevereVulnerabilityForGroup(project, group),
        }));
    },
```

This bit needs to be removed.

1. Finally we need to fetch the vulnerabilities at instance and group level dashboards and pass it down to the `first_class_vulnerability_severities.vue` component. This needs a bit refactoring.

We need a mutation to allow moving epics between board lists, similar to exiting mutation that moves/repositions issues [`IssueMoveList`](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/master/app/graphql/mutations/boards/issues/issue_move_list.rb).

It could be similar to:

```graphql
mutation {
  epicMoveList(input: { groupPath: "group", iid: "3", boardId: "gid://gitlab/Board/15", fromListId: 6, toListId: 7}) {
    errors
  }
}
```

We need to create a service for moving an epic and add the mutation.

- [Follow-up Issue for repositioning](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/323194)

New GraphQL endpoint to allow fetching epics in board list

All epics from all lists:

```
query {
  group(fullPath: "group") {
    board(id: "gid://gitlab/Board/3") {
      name
      lists {
        node {
          id
          epics {
            nodes {
              title
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Epics from one list:
```
query {
  group(fullPath: "group") {
    board(id: "gid://gitlab/Board/3") {
      name
      list(id: "gid://gitlab/List/8") {
        id
        label {
          title
          color
        }
        epics {
          nodes {
            title
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Tasks

- [x] Add a new table to store epic boards (e.g. `epic_boards`) (https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/233436#note_425401673)
- [x] Create new GraphQL endpoint to expose Boards
- [x] Create new GraphQL endpoint to expose Lists in a Board
- [x] Create new GraphQL endpoint to expose Epics in a Board List
  - [x] Make sure that relevant indexes (relative_position) are created when listing epics

The following discussion from !38315 should be addressed:

- [ ] @philipcunningham started a [discussion](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/38315#note_388590648):  (+4 comments)

    > @pgascouvaillancourt this is taking shape :bow: 
    > 
    > i've added some comments and suggestions above but i think there might be a slightly more systemic issue in that all of our graphql endpoints for `dast_site_profiles` and `dast_on_demand_scans` deal with global ids (e.g. `"gid://gitlab/DastSiteProfile/3"`) whereas the code you're using here relies on primary keys of the db tables.
    > 
    > you could extract the primary key from global id in the graphql response but i don't know if this is a common pattern on the ~frontend or not. that said, i wonder if it might make sense to add that graphql query to the ~backend for pulling sooner rather than later to ensure that we can fit everything together. wdyt?

